at are examining the actions of Washington lobbyist Jack Abramoff and public relations associate Mike Scanlon.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="23,29,30,55"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041001.0344"><line>Abramoff's high-ranking place in the capital's conservative hierarchy, and reports of a federal criminal investigation, have raised the profile of this particular scandal beyond that of the routine influence-peddling flap.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>He supported a resolution saying that the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks &quot;have created an urgent need for the continued services&quot; of Abramoff's firm.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>The closing of the Speaking Rock Casino near El Paso in February 2002 was one of John Cornyn's proudest moments as Texas attorney general.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>A spokesman for Feeney expressed surprise.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>He said each wireless company was sent a ballot and allowed to vote for LGC, Foxcom or &quot;no preference.&quot;</line><line>Abramoff suggested to Schwartz that the tribe send $50,000 to a charity he directed, the Capital Athletic Foundation, which would pay for the trip &quot;as an educational mission.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>&quot;It was the Congressman's understanding that this trip was permissible under House rules,&quot; said Brian J. Walsh, communications director for Ney.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051102.0241"><line>McCain said he hoped to introduce legislation next week to address some of the abuses.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Two months later, on Oct. 8, after the election bill came out of a House-Senate conference committee without a Tigua provision, Ney held a conference call with tribal officials and told them of his &quot;disbelief that