 the 18-member House of Representatives in the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="33"><scu uid="25" label="Abramoff's activities in Northern Marianas investigated" weight="3"/></annotation></line><line>His government work had been suspended for more than a year when DeLay's former aides came to the islands before Christmas 1999.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041001.0344"><line>&quot;Even in this town, where huge sums are routinely paid as the price of political access, the figures are astonishing,&quot; McCain said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>However, the Tiguas say no one told them the matter was closed.</line><line>Ney's remarks were orchestrated by Michael Scanlon, a former DeLay spokesman who had just been hired to work for Abramoff at Preston Gates &amp; Ellis LLP.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>Asked about Abramoff's alleged double-dealings with the Tigua, Cornyn said, &quot;Without prejudging, I find it somewhat disturbing.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>The matter was then closed from my perspective.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041001.0344"><line>&quot;All told, six tribes paid more than $66 million to Mr. Scanlon, and Mr. Abramoff received more than $21 million from Mr. Scanlon for his share of the scheme,&quot; Campbell said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Ney said he was not &quot;even remotely aware that any Indian tribe played any role (in his trip to Scotland).&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>He noted the audits and added that newspapers on the islands had reported this week that Fitial admitted he had won the speakership because of the work by DeLay's associates.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>The tribe did not want to pay.</line><line>He had nothing to do with later efforts to reopen it, Few said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041001.0344"><line>Then the two GOP insiders would step in and offer, for mighty fees, to smooth things over in Washington.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050429.0159"><line>Phone calls placed Friday night to Hart's Capitol Hill office and a home listing in Pennsylvania were not returned.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>Those activities included a 1998 trip arranged for Tom DeLay, the House majority leader, who is facing ethical questions about his relationship with Abramoff.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Palacios was a sponsor of that resolution.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Department of Justice and Indian Affairs Committee officials declined to discuss their investigations.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="5" label="Abramoff was Investigated by the Senate Indian Affairs Committee" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>Senate investigators discovered that the fees secretly were shared with Abramoff.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051102.0241"><line>They said Scanlon had written them that &quot;with the Enron and Continental Airlines debacles hitting the Houston area, they are desperate for revenue....</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>The statement noted that Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the Indian Affairs Committee, said Wednesday there was no evidence of any wrongdoing by Norton.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051118.1118"><line>Court papers filed by prosecutors say that Scanlon and the lobbyist &quot;sought and received Representative No. 1's agreement to perform a series of official acts.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Five weeks after the Boulis killing, SunCruz officials, including Kidan, threw a $1,000-a-head fund-raiser for Ney at Abramoff's skybox at the MCI Center, according to Abramoff's fund-raising log.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>A consultant to one tribal client of Abramoff testified that the lobbyist told him he needed $100,000 to pay for Ney and his contingent's golf trip to Scotland.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="13,21"><scu uid="33" label="Abramoff investigated in connection with golf junket" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>The contract was one of several totaling about $9 million given to Abramoff and his associates that have provoked questions about the lobbyist's activities in the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>Wednesday's hearing focused on whether Abramoff, when working for the Coushatta Tribe of Louisiana, relied on Griles to influence the Interior Department to block a rival tribe from opening a casino that would compete with the Coushattas' gaming business.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>As federal officials pursue a wide-ranging investigation into the activities of Washington lobbyist Jack Abramoff, his arrest on fraud charges in the purchase of a Florida casino boat company has increasingly focused attention on a little-known congressman from rural Ohio.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="7" sums="10,14,25,30,36,51,55"><scu uid="25" label="Abramoff's activities in Northern Marianas investigated" weight="3"/><scu uid="71" label="Abramoff and Scanlon investigations led to other investigations" weight="1"/><scu uid="71" label="Abramoff and Scanlon investigations led to other investigations" weight="1"/><scu uid="55" label="Abramoff arrested on fraud charges stemming from Florida deal" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051102.0241"><line>Abramoff and Scanlon are also being investigated by the Justice Department.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>He said &quot;a review of Justice Department records indicates that Mr. Abramoff never met with the attorney general or me during our services there.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Also that same year, a decision was delayed on the antennas, which caught House staff by surprise.</line><line>Ney later said he did not know about Kidan's background.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051102.0241"><line>He diverted $1.4 million to pay for work on his house and personal expenses, the committee found.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051118.1118"><line>In a widening scandal affecting Congress, the U.S. government charged a partner of a major Republican lobbyist with defrauding Indian tribes of millions of dollars in a scheme that lavished golf trips, meals and campaign donations on a member of Congress.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="6" sums="0,11,21,33,41,49"><scu uid="33" label="Abramoff investigated in connection with golf junket" weight="2"/><scu uid="42" label="Abramoff lobbying for Indian tribes benefitted  lobbyists" weight="1"/><scu uid="48" label="Scanlon lobbying for  Indian tribes benefitted political associates" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>The no-bid contract to promote &quot;ethics in government&quot; was awarded in 1996 to David Lapin, a rabbi whom the lobbyist, Jack Abramoff, later hired to run a now-defunct private Jewish school in the Washington suburbs.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>The trip cost $70,000 for DeLay and his entourage, records show.</line><line>Abramoff was on its board of directors from 1995 to 2004 and some of his tribal clients were among its major backers.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>That review, the statement said, &quot;precludes further comment on these issues.&quot;</line></docume