n addition, at the time of Ney's trip, the Scottish Parliament was out for its August recess, spokeswoman Sally Coyne said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051118.1118"><line>It has been a matter of public record for more than a year that Scanlon and Abramoff had a fee-splitting arrangement and represented several Indian tribes.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>McCain's hearings and newspaper accounts have raised questions about trips Abramoff arranged for lawmakers, including Ney and Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="39" label="Rep Robert Ney implicated" weight="2"/><scu uid="39" label="Rep Robert Ney implicated" weight="2"/><scu uid="23" label="Congressmen investigated for connection to Abramoff" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>In a statement last week, the Center said it paid for DeLay, his wife, Christine, and others to visit London and meet with British political leaders.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050429.0159"><line>DeLay, of Texas, is under scrutiny for overseas trips organized by Jack Abramoff, the lobbyist, whose far-reaching political work is now the subject of a federal grand jury investigation.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="13,20,23"><scu uid="22" label="DeLay investigated for connection to Abramoff" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Following Abramoff's instructions, the Alabama-Coushatta tribe, through its casino, made out a check for $50,000 payable to a foundation controlled by the lobbyist.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Abramoff, whose attorneys declined to comment for this article, has publicly denied that he misled Ney.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051102.0241"><line>Scanlon charged the Coushatta of Louisiana $1.3 million to set up a data base and then paid $104,000 to another firm to construct the computer file.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>But Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., author of the Senate version of the election reform bill, refused to add special language to the bill.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>The Lapin brothers are from South Africa and met Abramoff on one of his trips there.</line><line>The DeLay associates wanted the two legislators to support the candidate of the garment industry, Ben Fitial, who was close to Abramoff, and promised that federal contracts to the islands would follow if they did.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>DeLay landed in trouble last month over a 2000 trip to Scotland with the lobbyist.</line><line>A spokesman for his attorney, Abbe Lowell, issued a brief response.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>The lobbyist turned that threat into an opportunity to demonstrate his potential value, saying he could help thwart such efforts and would be seeing the attorney general in a week.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>(Optional add end)</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Times researcher Mark Madden in Washington also contributed to this report.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Foxcom officials have declined to be interviewed about the donation or the wireless project.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>According to McCain, the tribes paid Abramoff and Scanlon at least $66 million to advance gaming and other interests.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>&quot;Just met with Ney!!!</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Both men took the Fifth Amendment at the hearings.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Researcher Alice Crites and database editor Derek Willis contributed to this report.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Instead, the Tiguas arranged for their share of junket expenses to come from the Alabama-Coushatta, the other Texas tribe that would benefit from special language proposed for the pending legislation, according to testimony and interviews.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>The Mariana Islands, a self-governing U.S. territory subject to acts of Congress, have proven to be a veritable treasure chest for Abramoff.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>There was no mention of the golf excursions that, according to documents and Senate testimony, were arranged by Abramoff.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051118.1118"><line>Ney has denied wrongdoing and started a legal defense fund.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>Reed denies knowing that he was being paid by Indian tribes.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Fitial denied the federal budget benefits were tied to his speakership vote.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>The tribal leaders who attended the meeting were pleased and impressed with the outcome, Schwartz said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>In audits in late 2001, the Marianas government said that it had overpaid for eight years of lobbying contracts with Abramoff, that he had been paid without a contract in some cases and that it had been difficult to justify his hiring based on what work he did.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041001.0344"><line>Abramoff is a leading GOP fund-raiser, having collected hundreds of thousands of dollars over the years for House Majority Leader Tom DeLay of Texas and other top Republicans.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>In August 2002, Ney and his party flew in a chartered jet to St. Andrews' fabled golf course with Abramoff.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>In March 2000, Ney used the Congressional Record to assail Boulis.</line><line>Abramoff and his business partner were trying to buy the cruise ship fleet from Konstantinos &quot;Gus&quot; Boulis, but Boulis was demanding unwelcome additional terms.</line><line>LGC Chief Operating Officer Alex Gray wrote Ney to complain about the &quot;highly politicized selection process&quot; that favored the Israeli company despite the House's &quot;Buy American&quot; posture.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>The center has issued several reports on environmental issues and charges that environmentalists have engaged in &quot;a jihad against corporate America.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Asked why he, a longtime Democrat would switch support to Fitial, the head of the rival Covenant Party, Palacios said, &quot;That's politics.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041001.0344"><line>Abramoff and Scanlon would allegedly work behind the scenes to scare Indian tribes into thinking that they were about to lose lucrative gaming franchises.</line><line>Throughout U.S. history, &quot;every kind of charlatan and every type of crook has deceived and exploited America's native sons and daughters,&quot; says Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>McCain, now chairman of the Senate Indian Affairs Committee, said those payments warrant additional investigation.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>Griles denied that he said the binder came from Abramoff, and said he never knew who had put it on his desk.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Controversy surrounding some of the lobbyist fees was first disclosed in a small newspaper in Louisiana, the Daily Town Talk of Alexandria, in 2003.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>&quot;I wish the situation was not as critical as it is, but unfortunately our enemies have not gone away, just been beaten back,&quot; he concluded.</line><line>&quot;They said they would lobby for money for the breakwater,&quot; he said of his meeting with Scanlon and Buckham.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>Reed, former executive director of the Christian Coalition, was hired by Abramoff, an old friend, who was working at the Greenberg Traurig law firm.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>The Washington Post reported last year that the trip was actually paid for by the Capital Athletic Foundation, which reported in tax records that it spent $150,225 on the trip.</line><line>A Ney spokesman recently said that money has been donated to Ohio charities.</line><line>A former teacher and public safety director for his hometown of Bellaire, Ney was an Ohio legislator in 1994 when he defeated the Democratic incumbent in the congressional district once represented by Wayne Hays (D).</line><line>He said he was misled by Abramoff and his associates.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>&quot;Maybe lobbyists were engaged in self-promotion.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Mendiola, who no longer serves in the CNMI House, said he was promised federal assistance but denied any specific project was mentioned.</line><line>Abramoff donated $5,000 to Fitial's campaign, records show.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>The project was one of the largest of its kind, worth more than $3 million.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>&quot;I, of course, had filed the lawsuit earlier on.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>DeLay traveled to Saipan, the Marianas capital,, with his family in 1998 on a trip arranged by Abramoff, who billed the island government for the time his firm spent setting up the trip, records show.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>But in response to inquiries by the Times, the center said it did not provide &quot;a single dime&quot; for the Feeney junket.</line><line>Abramoff bragged of setting up the Scottish golf trip for his friend DeLay, according to Senate testimony and e-mails.</line><line>&quot;My heart goes out to the Indian tribes... who were duped,&quot; Ney said in his November statement.</line><line>Brooks is chief of staff to Rep. Jim McCrery, R-La., who was then fighting attempts of the Jena Band of Choctaw Indians to open a casino in his Louisiana district.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>&quot;Make no mistake about it, passage of that bill would kill jobs, growth and opportunity,&quot; DeLay said in a statement he put in the Congressional Record in 1997.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>Griles said the offer &quot;raised alarms with me,&quot; and he reported the incident to the Interior Department's ethics officer.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Spokesmen for the companies -- Cingular, Nextel, Sprint, Verizon Wireless, AT&amp;T Wireless and Voicestream -- said they remained neutral because both LGC and Foxcom were considered capable of doing the job.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>The Louisiana Coushattas paid Reed $3 million, fearing casino competition from another tribe in Louisiana and the expansion of gaming in Texas, which would probably draw gamblers away.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>He had filed personal bankruptcy, and he had surrendered his law license in New York after he was accused of fraud.</line><line>Soon after, in March 2002, Ney agreed to sponsor legislation that would benefit the Tigua tribe of El Paso, an Abramoff and Scanlon client.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="37,6"><scu uid="39" label="Rep Robert Ney implicated" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Once in office, the new speaker pressed the island's governor to re-instate an expired lobbying pact with Jack Abramoff, now under grand jury and congressional investigation.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="5" sums="14,23,30,32,44"><scu uid="71" label="Abramoff and Scanlon investigations led to other investigations" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Abramoff shot back by referring to the conference call when he spoke to the New York Times Magazine this spring.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051102.0241"><line>The two are accused of diverting millions of dollars from Indian tribes for personal use.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>The Republican majority leader lately has sought to distance himself from the besieged lobbyist he once called a close friend.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>The contributions at the May 29 event are a small part of the $9.8 million that Cornyn received in the 2002 race.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Ney later stated on disclosure forms filed with the House that the August 2002 trip cost $3,200 and was paid for by the National Center for Public Policy Research, a conservative advocacy group on whose board Abramoff served.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051102.0241"><line>&quot;While Indian country has seen many con-men through history, few were as skilled as Mr Abramoff and Mr. Scanlon at creating and preying upon insecurities,&quot;said Kevin Stickey, chairman of the Coushatta tribe, which runs the casino resort near Kinder, La.&quot;They exaggerated political threats, and they exaggerated economic threats.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Abramoff paid $72,000 from a personal business account to charter a jet in advance of the Ney trip, records released by a Senate committee show.</line><line>The criminal investigation appears to be a sweeping probe of Abramoff's lobby practice, based on interviews with witnesses and published accounts.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>The trip, Ney said in his statement last year, had nothing to do with legislation for the tribe.</line><line>Abramoff and his business partner Adam Kidan were indicted in August on fraud charges related to the purchase.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051118.1118"><line>DeLay left his leadership position because of the charges but has denied them.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Both said in separate interviews that Buckham and Scanlon promised to help get money for needed projects in their impoverished island districts.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050429.0159"><line>Hart, R-Pa., had been named by the House ethics committee chairman to look into accusations about DeLay months ago, before the ethics panel became deadlocked earlier this year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>&quot;We haven't been able to figure out what the deliverables were,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051102.0241"><line>The Coushattas, who paid Abramoff and Scanlon $36 million in fees over three years, told the panel they feel betrayed by the lobbyists.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line><line>The tribal officials testified before the Senate Indian Affairs Committee, which is investigating the lobbying activities of Jack Abramoff and Michael Scanlon, a former spokesman for Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="11" sums="14,29,30,32,36,37,38,43,44,55,6"><scu uid="5" label="Abramoff was Investigated by the Senate Indian Affairs Committee" weight="1"/><scu uid="68" label="Michael Scanlon is DeLay's former aide" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>Abramoff later helped Daniel Lapin found Toward Tradition, a Seattle group that describes itself as working &quot;against anti-religion bigotry,&quot; and remains a board member.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Abramoff's prominent lobbying career crashed last year after the Senate Committee on Indian Affairs accused him and Scanlon of ripping off six Indian tribes who had paid them $66 million.<annotation scu-count="6" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"><scu uid="1" label="Jack Abramoff is a  GOP lobbyist" weight="4"/><scu uid="1" label="Jack Abramoff is a  GOP lobbyist" weight="4"/><scu uid="6" label="Lobbyist Jack Abramoff has an associate Michael Scanlon" weight="3"/><scu uid="6" label="Lobbyist Jack Abramoff has an associate Michael Scanlon" weight="3"/><scu uid="41" label="Abramoff charged by Senate Indian Affairs for bilking millions" weight="2"/><scu uid="41" label="Abramoff charged by Senate Indian Affairs for bilking millions" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041001.0344"><line>At the center of the scandal is Jack Abramoff, a GOP lobbyist and longtime friend and political associate of some of his party's most gifted strategists, including Ralph Reed, the former head of the Christian Coalition and the Southern regional chairman for President Bush's re-election campaign, and noted conservative activist Grover Norquist.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>A November hearing focused on Scanlon and Abramoff splitting $4.2 million in fees to help the Tiguas, a Texas tribe hard-hit when the state closed their casino.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>He warned that the territory was in jeopardy.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>David Safavian, then chief of staff at the General Services Administration, also went on the trip with Ney, Abramoff and former Christian Coalition leader Ralph Reed Jr. Safavian, who went on to become the chief White House procurement officer, was indicted this month on charges that he lied to investigators looking into the Scotland trip when he said that Abramoff had no business before the his agency.<annotation scu-count="11" sum-count="1" sums="3"><scu uid="39" label="Rep Robert Ney implicated" weight="2"/><scu uid="39" label="Rep Robert Ney implicated" weight="2"/><scu uid="73" label="Ralph Reed implicated" weight="1"/><scu uid="73" label="Ralph Reed implicated" weight="1"/><scu uid="73" label="Ralph Reed implicated" weight="1"/><scu uid="66" label="Safavian impilcated" weight="1"/><scu uid="66" label="Safavian impilcated" weight="1"/><scu uid="66" label="Safavian impilcated" weight="1"/><scu uid="40" label="Safavian indicted in connection with a golf trip" weight="1"/><scu uid="40" label="Safavian indicted in connection with a golf trip" weight="1"/><scu uid="40" label="Safavian indicted in connection with a golf trip" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041001.0344"><line>&quot;Shortly after... they solicited and received multimillion-dollar contracts, aided by the tribal council members they helped elect.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>He said there was concern in some quarters that island immigration rules, favoring the garment industry, could be exploited by terrorists.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>It gets most of its revenue through direct mail solicitations, records show, and boasts of receiving no public funding.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>The deal closed in the fall.</line><line>In a letter to Betz, LGC president and chief executive Ian Sugarbroad called the election process &quot;deeply flawed and unfair.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>The Tigua casino never reopened.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>DeLay, then a member of the House Appropriations Committee, was on the conference committee approving the allocation.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>McCain's hearings have focused on Abramoff's dealings with six tribes.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="25"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>It was recorded as a charitable contribution to the Capital Athletic Foundation, according to tax records.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Meanwhile, Ney accepted many favors from Abramoff, among them campaign contributions, dinners at the lobbyist's downtown restaurant, skybox fund-raisers, including one at his MCI Center box here, and a golfing trip to Scotland in August 2002.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>&quot;It was nice to receive that support, but it didn't have much to do with what we were already doing.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>A spokesman for Abramoff also declined to answer questions.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>Despite Cornyn's image as a gaming foe, he received $6,250 in contributions for his 2002 race from Las Vegas casino interests, according to the Center for Responsive Politics, which compiled data from the Federal Election Commission.</line><line>In a series of e-mails released by the Senate Indian Affairs Committee, Cornyn's name appears numerous times in communications among Reed, Abramoff and Scanlon.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>&quot;Please urge Teno to execute the agreement as we will continue to encounter problems... if the contract is not executed.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>Investigations into his activities have led to one indictment of a onetime government official; the former head of procurement for the General Services Administration, David Safavian, has been charged with making false statements and obstruction of justice in connection with a golf trip Abramoff took in 2002 with Rep. Bob Ney, R-Ohio, and others.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051102.0241"><line>The lobbyists also worked against the tribe's interest, according to a Senate investigation that uncovered an e-mail from Abramoff to an associate in which he suggested trying to obtain the business of the Alabama Coushatta, who wanted to open a rival casino in Texas.</line><line>According to tribal officials, the Coushatta funneled $400,000 in funds through third parties, who then paid Reed.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Safavian, who has since been appointed chief of procurement at the Office of Management and Budget by President Bush, said he wrote a personal check to Abramoff.</line><line>Ney came to Abramoff's aid two years earlier on another case.</line><line>Like House members, staff aides are required to file reports on trips sponsored by outside parties and may not accept travel financed or arranged by lobbyists.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>&quot;Since my previous statement, I have come to learn that SunCruz Casino now finds itself under new ownership and, more importantly, that its new owner has a renowned reputation for honesty and integrity,&quot; Ney said in the Congressional Record on Oct. 26, 2000.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Abramoff said the official tipped him off about a secret internal document that might jeopardize CNMI's cherished immigration exemptions.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>The Louisiana Coushattas, who paid Abramoff and Scanlon more than $30 million, have sued Abramoff, Scanlon, and Greenberg Traurig, accusing them of a variety of abuses, including fraud, overbilling and negligence.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>It drew national attention after reports last year in the Washington Post.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Despite his success, however, Abramoff's lobbying arrangement with the Northern Marianas government ended in late 1998, according to official lobbying reports, because of a change in administrations and commonwealth fiscal problems.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>They wanted Ney's help to reopen the Tiguas' casino, which the state of Texas had shut down.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>The public dispute between the two offered a dramatic close to hearings that have explored the complex web of influence, money and access Abramoff wove as one of Washington most well-connected lobbyists.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>&quot;I then (in July 2002) personally asked Senator Dodd about this provision and he expressed no knowledge of it,&quot; Ney said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Abramoff's billing records, recently made public by the Marianas government, show how the lobbyist used the islands to woo Washington friends and then used those Washington friends to woo his island clients.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Congressmen routinely travel as guests of educational and policy groups, but they cannot accept trips and gifts from lobbyists.</line><line>Checks totaling $32,000 were sent.Two months later, Abramoff asked the Tiguas to pay half of Ney's golf junket to Scotland.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="43,57"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>&quot;My concern is that he's working with Ralph Reed, who's being paid by Indian gaming interests,&quot; Sloan said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>But Kidan's &quot;track record&quot; included a string of lawsuits, judgments, liens, bankruptcies and failed businesses.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050429.0159"><line>Since Republicans agreed earlier this week to rescind rules that had made it more difficult to open an ethics investigation, Hastings has not said whether Hart would still direct any review.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>The Fitial-led House also passed two resolutions urging the governor to hire a lobbyist, including a July 26, 2000, resolution calling for selection of Abramoff's firm.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Ney has said he was misled by Abramoff about who paid for the trip.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="18,22,49"><scu uid="39" label="Rep Robert Ney implicated" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>The Oct. 1, 2001, memo was written as Abramoff's final contract with the islands was winding down.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>And like Ney, Feeney reported that the National Center was the sponsor of the August 2003 trip, picking up a tab of $5,643.</line><line>DeLay bristled when asked last week about the Britain trip, saying he reported it properly.He brushed aside questions about the lobbyist, saying that &quot;Jack Abramoff is not the only person I talk to in Washington, D.C. I have a lot of relationships, hundreds of relationships.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>The latest disclosures coming out of the Pacific islands add fuel to the yearlong political scandal swirling around Abramoff and his ties to congressional leaders, especially DeLay.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Ney is under investigation by Florida federal prosecutors looking into Abramoff's acquisition of SunCruz, according to sources familiar with the investigation who spoke on the condition of anonymity.</line><line>But to members of Congress, Ney is known as the mayor of Capitol Hill.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>In an interview, Cornyn said he was &quot;unaware&quot; of Reed's role in Texas although he knew Reed from GOP political circles.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>During the next year, LGC worked with the architect of the Capitol and the House Information Resources office to develop a plan.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Abramoff also told the consultant that he had arranged a similar golf trip for DeLay in 2000, according to the testimony.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051118.1118"><line>The Scanlon case, closely tied to Republican politicians, has the potential of becoming another headache for the party.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051102.0241"><line>The Coushatta paid the firm run by former Christian Coalition director Ralph Reed to drum up opposition to gambling among ministers and other social conservatives in Texas.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Abramoff, among the most powerful Republican lobbyists on Capitol Hill over the last decade, is the focus of inquiries by a federal grand jury and a U.S. Senate committee.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>Abramoff's biggest year, according to the audit, was 1997, when Preston Gates earned $3.1 million from the territory.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Three years later a bill that would have barred the use of &quot;Made in USA&quot; by the island's apparel industry was never even brought up for a House vote though it had 234 co-sponsors, more than a majority.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>&quot;We did not know of any specific clients or any specific interests involved.</line><line>I was doing my duty to enforce the law.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>At the time, LGC was the world's leading provider of such equipment and had wired the headquarters of most cellular phone companies, including Nextel and AT&amp;T.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041001.0344"><line>&quot;In at least two instances, Mr. Abramoff and Mr. Scanlon sought to profit by becoming involved in and attempting to manipulate tribal elections,&quot; said Campbell.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>We're f'ing gold!!!!</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>The lobbyist also opposed the proposed gaming facility because it would have competed with a client's casino.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>A spokesman for DeLay said Scanlon was on unpaid leave at the time of the trip, but records show he did not leave the payroll until January 2000.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>Griles said he was surprised when Abramoff introduced him to a partner in Greenberg Traurig, the lobbying company Abramoff worked for, who offered him a job at the end of a brief meeting.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="22"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>During the 2002 campaign, Cornyn attended a fund-raiser at the home of Las Vegas entertainer Wayne Newton in an event organized by Sen. John Ensign, R-Nev.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Five of them were interviewed by The Post, and the sixth made its preference known in a letter obtained by The Post.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>&quot;That is outrageous... and it is not true,&quot; Griles said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050429.0159"><line>The campaign records showed the event at Abramoff's restaurant was held on Sept. 24, 2003, and that the payments went toward &quot;catering costs.&quot;</line><line>Campaign watchdog groups said Friday that it would be inappropriate for Rep. Melissa A. Hart to oversee any potential inquiry of the House majority leader, Tom DeLay, because she had received $15,000 from his political action committee and held a fund-raiser at a restaurant owned by a Republican lobbyist at the center of a growing corruption scandal.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="51"><scu uid="54" label="Abramoff and Scanlon at center of corruption scandal" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>Griles, Rosetti said, wanted him to make sure Norton saw the file.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>And, like the Texas Republican, all omitted disclosing the key role of embattled lobbyist Jack Abramoff.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Assistant House Counsel Carolyn Betz, replying on behalf of Ney, said in a letter to LGC that in the fall of 2001 the major wireless companies were receiving ballots to vote on who should get the contract.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>In a 2002 interview with The New York Times, Abramoff said he first met DeLay through Daniel Lapin, who would meet frequently with members of Congress to press conservative causes.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Both aides listed the National Center as their trip sponsor, although the nonprofit agency also flatly disputed that.</line><line>Early details of Abramoff's role in the golf junkets emerged during a Senate hearing in November.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>One of Abramoff's strong local allies and supporters was Benigno Fitial, an underdog contender for speaker of the House.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Heaton reported to the House that his trip had been sponsored by the National Center.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>A few months later, Boulis agreed in principle to sell SunCruz to Abramoff and Kidan for $147.5 million.</line><line>In early 2002, Volz left his post as Ney's chief of staff to join Abramoff's lobbying team.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>It also allowed us to acquire some very powerful allies such as (then) Majority Whip Tom DeLay.&quot;</line><line>&quot;They (Department of Justice officials) have been spending a week or so telling everyone who will listen that the CNMI, if it is not taken over, will be a major entry point for terrorists.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050429.0159"><line>&quot;She also needs to overcome the reality that she accepted $15,000 from one of Mr. DeLay's political action committees.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>DeLay, whose foreign travel arranged by lobbyists has drawn criticism in Congress for possible ethical violations, visited the Marianas in 1998 with his wife and daughter and three aides.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>In 2003, he joined the House speaker and other Republican leaders signing a letter to U.S. Interior Secretary Gale A. Norton.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Tigua consultant Schwartz later testified to the Senate Indian Affairs Committee that Ney remained a strong supporter of the Tigua legislation and Abramoff long after his conversation with Dodd.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services at www.star-telegram.com) nn</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>J. Steven Griles, Interior's former deputy secretary, told the Senate Indian Affairs Committee that he had no special relationship with Abramoff and gave him no special access, as the lobbyist has claimed in e-mails and at least one interview.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>&quot;I too was misled,&quot; he said, by Abramoff and Scanlon whom he called &quot;these two nefarious individuals.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Details of the overseas mission and the trade of political favors nearly half the globe from Capitol Hill, come from interviews, government documents and e-mails reviewed by the Los Angeles Times.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Both Abramoff, 46, and Scanlon, 34, took the Fifth Amendment and refused to answer questions before the Senate in the fall.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Island records show efforts were under way to provide federal funding for an airport repaving project on Rota, the island Mendiola represented.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Rep. Robert W. Ney, R-Ohio, placed comments in the Congressional Record favorable to Abramoff's 2000 purchase of the casino boat company, SunCruz Casinos.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Ney was the bill's author and as committee chairman would be part of the House-Senate conference committee determining its final language.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>On June 7, 2002, Abramoff sent an e-mail to Tigua consultant Marc Schwartz wrote that &quot;our friend&quot; had &quot;asked if we could help (as in cover) a Scotland golf trip for him and some staff.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>Abramoff and Scanlon had many Indian gaming clients, including the Tigua Ysleta de Sur Pueblo, as the Tigua are known.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>He asked them to send it by Federal Express.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Ney became chairman of the committee thanks to his political patron, Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who recently stepped down as House majority leader after he was indicted on a charge of conspiracy to violate a Texas campaign law.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Although the contract was renewed shortly after that e-mail, the reprieve was temporary.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>&quot;We were really surprised, given all the work we put in with LGC in designing the system,&quot; said Henry F. &quot;Bud&quot; Collins Jr., the senior network systems engineer for the House.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>In May 2000, the Rota runway resurfacing project was among the airport projects that the House Appropriations Committee directed should be given priority for discretionary grants in the Federal Aviation Administration budget for 2001, according to the committee report on the bill.</line><line>&quot;This is starting to smell more like criminal activity -- trading congressional appropriations for votes,&quot; said U.S. Rep. George Miller, D-Calif.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>That year Ney took a trip to Montenegro sponsored by a foundation that had links to Abramoff, who was a lobbyist for Montenegro.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051118.1118"><line>Michael Scanlon, an ex-aide to former House Majority Leader Tom DeLay, is headed for federal court Monday on a conspiracy count contained in a criminal information.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041001.0344"><line>He is also among the elite group of &quot;Pioneers&quot; who pledged to raise more than $100,000 for Bush's re-election campaign this year.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>Whose water was he carrying?&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>In a statement issued this week a Delay spokesman said the legislation that the majority leader opposed &quot;would have strangled the (Marianas') burgeoning economy.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Since the golf trip, DeLay has continued to help Abramoff's clients.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="25"><scu uid="22" label="DeLay investigated for connection to Abramoff" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>&quot;In short, I had been misled by Jack Abramoff.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>In one 2001 memo, Abramoff bragged to Marianas officials about an unnamed top U.S. Department of Justice official who was the lobbyist's guest at his box seat for a Washington Redskin game.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>In 1999, DeLay's former chief of staff, Edwin Buckham, and his former spokesman, Michael Scanlon, both of whom later worked with Abramoff in his lobbying firm, visited the islands to persuade two local lawmakers to change their votes for speaker of the islands' House of Representatives.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Abramoff then arranged for his charity to pay for the trip, according to documents released by a Senate committee investigating the lobbyist.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="29,37,6"/></line><line>Before the meeting, &quot;in an e-mail to me, Abramoff mentioned that Congressman Ney didn't want his trip to Scotland brought up, as he would show his appreciation to the Tribe later,&quot; Schwartz testified.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Buckham declined to respond to detailed questions.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Six days later Abramoff directed tribal officials to make three contributions totaling $32,000 to Ney's campaign and political action committees.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="39" label="Rep Robert Ney implicated" weight="2"/><scu uid="47" label="Abramoff lobbying for Indian tribes benefitted political associates" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>For example, the lobbyist and his law firm routinely arranged for congressional junkets to the islands, despite ethics rules barring such practices.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>He has pleaded not guilty.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0261"><line>In addition, Abramoff had lobbying contracts with the textile industry trade group there.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="25,32"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Ney is House Administration Committee chairman, a powerful position that doles out budgets, equipment, offices and parking spaces to House members.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051102.0151"><line>The Abramoff investigation is one of several ethical headaches confronting the GOP that Democrats have charged add up to a culture of corruption in official Washington -- most recently the indictment of Vice President Dick Cheney's chief of staff, I. Lewis &quot;Scooter&quot; Libby, in connection with the probe of the leak of a covert CIA officer's identity.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>A year after the Ney trip, Abramoff was headed back to Scotland on a chartered jet with Rep. Feeney.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="37,6"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>Schwartz said that in August 2002 -- a month after Ney's reported conversation with Dodd and around the time of the Scotland trip -- Abramoff arranged for Ney to meet with Tigua representatives in his office.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>Get me details so I can alert Cornyn and let him know what we are doing to help him.&quot;</line><line>However, in an e-mail sent Jan. 7, 2002, there is the suggestion that Reed knew who he was working for.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>Justice Department spokesman Mark Corallo said that Ashcroft never met with Abramoff and attributed the references in the memo to &quot;a lot of bluster to impress a client.&quot;</line><line>He wants Congress to make it easier for island garment manufacturers to satisfy requirements for claiming it was &quot;Made in USA&quot; -- reducing the locally produced content from 50 percent to only 30 percent.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051102.0241"><line>The Texas Legislature was considering, but never approved, gambling.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041001.0344"><line>The scheme generated so much money that, aside from pocketing millions of dollars, the lobbyists funneled hundreds of thousands of dollars to Republican candidates, and to the lobbyists' pals and pet causes.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>&quot;No! No! No! There was no -- I give you something, you give me something,&quot; Fitial said.</line><line>Please help!!&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>&quot;He was on the phone for an hour and a half!&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>The Choctaw tribe of Mississippi gave $1 million to the center, according to Senate testimony.</line><line>Tribal leaders told Senate and federal investigators that Abramoff pressured them to pay millions of dollars in fees to former DeLay aide, Michael Scanlon.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="3" sums="12,29,42"><scu uid="68" label="Michael Scanlon is DeLay's former aide" weight="1"/><scu uid="20" label="Abramoff and Scanlon bilked clients of millions of dollars" weight="1"/><scu uid="20" label="Abramoff and Scanlon bilked clients of millions of dollars" weight="1"/><scu uid="42" label="Abramoff lobbying for Indian tribes benefitted  lobbyists" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>His determination to shut down the Tigua Indian tribe's casino because it was opened in violation of state law earned the Texas Republican kudos and pledges of support from Christian political organizers -- backing that proved helpful as Cornyn made his successful run for the U.S. Senate that year.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Abramoff told tribal leaders that the Ohio congressman could attach language concerning their shuttered casino to an unrelated election reform bill.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>&quot;I want to be absolutely clear that at no point, ever, was I made even remotely aware that any Indian tribe played any role in this trip,&quot; Ney said in his statement.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050418.0210"><line>But Cornyn's role in the casino controversy is only beginning to draw attention.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050505.0164"><line>The workers, many brought in from China under less-restrictive immigration rules than in the rest of the United States and most of its territories, produce garments that are still stamped &quot;Made in USA,&quot; thanks, in part, to the efforts of Abramoff and DeLay.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051018.0002"><line>But representatives of all six companies said they voted no preference, according to interviews and documents.</line><line>Volz has repeatedly declined to be interviewed.</line><line>This spring, Ney hired a prominent Washington criminal defense lawyer, Mark Tuohey, to handle inquiries from the Justice Department and congressional investigators pursuing the widening scandal.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0163"><line>Corporate records list Abramoff and his wife, Pamela, as the foundation's sole directors.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051118.1118"><line>Among the people subpoenaed in the Scanlon and Abramoff investigation was Rep. Bob Ney, a Republican from Ohio, whose name surfaced almost a year ago in a Senate Indian Affairs Committee investigation as having extensive dealings with the two lobbyists and their tribal clients.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="1" sums="40"><scu uid="39" label="Rep Robert Ney implicated" weight="2"/><scu uid="39" label="Rep Robert Ney implicated" weight="2"/><scu uid="39" label="Rep Robert Ney implicated" weight="2"/><scu uid="39" label="Rep Robert Ney implicated" weight="2"/><scu